source.description:
Neural network with homogenous connectivity, expressing slow oscillations or asynchronous awake like regime. The models can be configured to run with static or plastic synapses or to switch between the two modes. Simulations with static synapses consume less memory.

The models can be configured to express Slow Wave Activity (SWA), Slow Oscillations (SO) or Asynchronous Awake like (AW) regimes, with static and plastic synapses, and different models of space dependent interconnects.

Abstraction level. Single compartment point-like neurons, (membrane potential and fatigue variables), static or plastic (STDP) synapses, programmable distance dependent connectivity, instantaneous synaptic currents.

Scientific purposes: this set of models serves a set of scientific purposes, including:

- a preliminary investigation of the interaction between SWA/SO and STDP causal plasticity. Follow this link for these configurations.
- scalability studies and investigation of co-design techniques (software and interconnect architectures) for better scalability on large-scale distributed computing platforms
- investigation of the impact of biologically realistic interconnects and neural and synaptic densities on the scaling of distributed simulations.
- investigation of power consumption and real-rime issued in large scale cortical simulations

Fabrizio Capuani, Maurizio Mattia, Elena Pastorelli, Francesco Simula and Pier Stanislao Paolucci (2018) "Multi-scale simulations of SWA, SO and AW regimes, with static and plastic synapses." https://collab.humanbrainproject.eu/#/collab/11175/nav/83589

images.caption: Fig. 1. Snapshot of a slow wave propagating on a 96x96 grid of cortical modules. The model includes a total of 11.5M neurons and 17.5G and executes on a distributed platform including 1024 Intel cores HPC

source.name: Multi-scale NN for SWA, SO and AW
